# .semgrepignore
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Files excluded from Semgrep SAST scanning.
# Semgrep respects .gitignore by default; this file adds project-specific
# suppressions on top of that.
#
# Format: same glob syntax as .gitignore
# Docs: https://semgrep.dev/docs/ignoring-files-folders-code/
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Intentionally vulnerable files ───────────────────────────────────────────
# insecureRoutes.js and insecureGraphQL.js contain deliberate SQL injection
# vulnerabilities. They are intentionally included in scanning so Semgrep
# confirms it can detect the vulnerability patterns. The pipeline is expected
# to FAIL on these findings — that is the correct and desired behaviour.

# ── Dependencies ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
node_modules/
frontend/node_modules/
backend/node_modules/

# ── Build output ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
frontend/build/

# ── Archived legacy files (old AWS / Helm / CodeBuild deployment path) ────────
# Archive/ holds infra/, DevSecOps/, buildspec.yml and other artefacts from the
# earlier AWS/EKS approach. None of it runs in the current stack. Excluding to
# prevent false positives and noise in SAST results.
Archive/

# ── Terraform state/cache (belt-and-suspenders alongside .gitignore) ──────────
terraform/**/.terraform/

# ── K8s database deployment ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# k8s/db/deployment.yaml runs PostgreSQL which requires runAsNonRoot: false.
# Postgres manages its own internal user (uid 999) and the container entrypoint
# must start as root to set up data directory permissions before dropping privileges.
# The inline # nosemgrep comment on line 59 was suppressing this correctly, but
# Semgrep community rule IDs are not stable across versions. File-level exclusion
# is more robust for a pre-existing, documented accepted risk.
k8s/db/deployment.yaml
